  "prompt": "What is the difference between wires and cables?",
  "response": "Wires and cables are both used to transmit electricity or data, but there are some differences between the two.\n\nA wire is a single strand or a group of strands of an electrically conductive material, usually metal, such as copper or aluminum. Wires are typically used in electrical systems, such as home wiring, and can be found in a range of sizes and gauges.\n\nA cable, on the other hand, is a group of wires, usually insulated and bound together within an outer jacket. The jacket provides protection and can be made of different materials, such as rubber or plastic, depending on the cable's intended use. Cables can transmit power, data, or both and are commonly used in applications such as telecommunications, networking, and audio/visual systems.\n\nIn summary, wires are single conductors, while cables are assemblies of multiple wires. Cables are often used for more complex applications and are designed to be more durable and protective than individual wires.",
